 both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Walthers","meanings":["German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Walther</i> (see   Walter  )."]},{"name":"McQuate","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uait</b> ‘son of <i>Uat</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Irish form   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waltke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Jurgen, Wilhelmina.","German: from a pet form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with Old High German <i>waltan</i> ‘to rule’ as the first element, as in   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McWaters","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the personal name   Walter  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wahler","meanings":["German:","from the personal name <i>Wol(d)er</i>, Low German form of   Walter  .","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wahl, Wahle, or Wahlen."]},{"name":"McWalter","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b> ‘son of   Walter  ’."]},{"name":"Walters","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Walther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Wolfgang, Otto, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Bernd, Bernhard.","German, Dutch, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Lauter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Erwin, Kurt, Sigismund, Wolf.","German: topographic name and habitational name, from a common stream name meaning ‘clear’, from Middle High German <i>hlutra</i>, or from any of the places called Lauter or Lauta (Saxony). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and some other European countries.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lavtar</b> or its Croatized and rare Slovenian variant <b>Lautar</b>: from a dialect variant of the personal name <i>Valter</i> (see   Walter  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705206,"age":1,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":15,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":17,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Walter was born about 1570, in Gloucestershire, England. He had a